nullspace

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
-7 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 3 & 0 \\
-2 & 0 &-4
\end{bmatrix}
- 
\begin{bmatrix}
-5 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -5 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -5
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
-2 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 8 & 0 \\
-2 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

and from this we can see that

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
0 \\
2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

is an eigenvector associated to $\lambda = -5$ (to get all eigenvectors,
multiply this vector by any non-zero number). Repeating this with
$\displaystyle \lambda = -6$

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
-7 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 3 & 0 \\
-2 & 0 &-4
\end{bmatrix}
- 
\begin{bmatrix}
-6 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -6 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -6
\end{bmatrix} = 
\begin{bmatrix}
-1 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 9 & 0 \\
-2 & 0 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

and from this we can see that

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
0 \\
1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

is an eigenvector associated to $\lambda = -6$ (to get all eigenvectors,
multiply this vector by any non-zero number).

